comments: This is the first Die Hard film I was old enough to see at the theater.  No, it's not anywhere near as good as the first Die Hard (what is?), but I saw this at a Midnight screening after a Prince concert back in 2007, and after the high of that concert this was one of my favourite filmgoing experiences.  Yes, some of the set-pieces are very silly and it lacks the relative credibility of the first Die Hard or even Die Hard with a Vengeance, but this is still fun, the Willis and Justin Long interplay is highly enjoyable, and Timothy Olyphant is arguably the best Die Hard villain after the brilliant Alan Rickman (Jeremy Irons was good too, but I don't think he was quite as nasty as Rickman and Olyphant's characters).

comments:
Rotten Tomatoes ranks this at 40%, with an overall consensus that seems to be more confused than definitive, praising it for being slick and well acted but not quite good enough.

Honestly... Closed Circuit is a movie that carries a great spy vibe to it. This is in part because it is a thriller but also in part to some of the plots characters. Bana and Hall are average at best, i mean its no Munich...thats for sure. But i found myself more approving of Bana than Hall, but thats just favoritism. Cirian Hinds has a nice minor supporting role as well as Broadbent, but ultimately are not enough to bring the movie home.
It has a great plot, it has great thriller elements to it, its suspenseful and somewhat plausible but i think what really hampers this film is its abrupt stop.
There is a point in the film, about a quarter of the way through, where one character mentions something that if it were enacted in the film, could easily stop the movie in its tracks, but for our sake allows it to continue on right up untill the climax.
when said event finally does take place you feel sort of duped. In a sense it was as if the movie told us the multiple ways it could end and the for some reason chose the least interesting way for it to end.
It is for sure worth a redbox at the least. check it out

comments: The Illusionist (2006) should be watched with The Prestige (2006).

I've always enjoyed what magicians can do & though i have had plenty of chances to see how these illusions have been done them i prefer not to know as your spoiling the whole object of what the magician is doing & thats trying to entertain you all the while you are left to try & figure out how those tricks were done...

I & 2 of my friends went to see a scottish mentalist who could hypnotize those who were susceptible to this & i'll stress that it was the audience complete choice to take part in this as you had to clasp your hands together & after he said what he wanted & you if couldn't separate your hands this showed you were susceptible to being hypnotized & even then you didnt need to participate unless you wanted to as once he had his volunteers as if by magic your hands were now free & i'll also point out that you had the option to not even clasps your hands & therefore you weren't forced into doing this whatsoever & it was completely up to those audience members if they wanted to participate or not at every opportunity...

If you havent gone to a show like this i recommend doing so as your have one hell of a laugh at the comical antics taking place on stage by volunteers from the audience...

That aside i always preferred " The Illusionist " to " The Prestige " & though both had great actor's who put convincing performances i preferred this film because the overall narrative was more compelling & to me had the better overall story...

If you haven't watched them or you've only watched one of them then i recommend watching both & then make up your own opinion as to what movie you liked the best...

In light of this still ongoing coronavirus stay safe & healthy wherever you are in this world...

What i can tell you is he went up on stage with other member's of the audience & i sat there & watched my friend do things he wouldnt do for a laugh if he was drunk & we left that show later on in absolute stitches as we couldnt stop laughing at how this mentalist managed to make these people perform such hilarious acts at his request & all those who took part were given free tickets to back & watched the show just as a viewer as they missed it because they were the show & couldnt remember anything...

comments: The reason the first one was scary was because it was the fear of the unknown. It hinted at the fact that there was something paranormal but it could have easily just been some teens trying to fuck with them, or some murderer, or ANYTHING. The movie hinted at so many possibilities at the beginning, with the creepy lady with a fence made out of twigs (like the stick men in the trees) and the two fishermen who knew a lot about the Blair witch, where it could have been any number of things that could have happened to them, not just something paranormal. This fucking movie not only is an attempt to bank off the original, but ruins what made the original scary, and takes away whatever people wanted to believe. comments: Wow gorgeous

People should really stop judging the movie before they see it, especially based off of the trailer. Movie trailers nowadays are like mini-films themselves. They're created by companies completely separate from the production team of the film itself. An entirely different group of people that weren't involved with the making of the film receive a rough copy of a movie and have to think of a way to present it to captivate the widest possible audience. They use many tactics to do this, and a lot of what goes into movie trailer production is a manipulation of the actual film itself. Scenes play out and are edited differently in trailers than in the actual film many times. So stop being so judgmental and wait for the actual film to come out before you say anything. And if you KNOW you're not going to see the film, why are you taking the time out of your day to post about it and be so negative instead of doing something else with your time? Are your comments even productive? There's a difference between giving and honest, constructive opinion of a film and simply saying "this looks awful lol" or "this will FLOP". At the very least elaborate, or don't speak!
